social_posts.post_text: Writing is hard. It can be lonely. But this week I’m so so thankful to say I had one of the most heartwarming days of work as an author I have ever had.  I was invited to my elementary school, Mission Avenue, for author day, which already gave me a healthy dose of imposter syndrome. So then I get there and the k-6th students had decorated the entire auditorium - the one I grew up going to assemblies in - with these incredible posters for @mop_rides and @city_of_dragons. Then I was told they were going to perform a student government skit before my presentation, and the students surprised me by performing a MOP play they wrote- replete with a magical dragon in full regalia. My outstanding 4th grade teacher Mrs. Carter - who was the first teacher to encourage me to write - stayed for all three of my presentations, as did some old friends. We sang songs together and drew  waves and dragons together. Vivian zoomed in from London to inspire us with stellar art. The kids drew fantastically and asked excellent questions, and when I asked who is writing their own comics or books, about 50 hands shot up. There’s a lot doom and gloom about education, but whenever I have the good fortune of spending time with kids in schools, I walk out feeling so optimistic. And Mission Avenue gave me that feeling exponentially. Thank you Mission Avenue PTA and teachers and parents and STUDENTS for such a beautiful day. I feel truly blessed.

It gets crazy hard to see your homies when you become a parent but it’s possible with a little creativity. Love that my buddy @alexanderjfang asked me to skate to pick up his 4 year-old Max today. Most memorable pickup ever. Thank you to everyone who is pushing to keep SF’s Great Highway for the people 🤙
Thought I’d mention this is holding true for me at 43! And still falling pretty much every day - on and off my board. Thanks @mop_rides and @mattallen_art for the reminder 🙏🏽🌊🙏🏽🌊

My interpretive gratitude dance to say thank you to our publisher @graphixbooks @scholasticinc for having faith in our @city_of_dragons series and buying books 3 & 4! Also, yes, Book 2 is coming!  @superrisu is coloring it now and it looks amazing. Can’t wait to share. Warning: more interpretive dances may result. Also thank you @markgottliebliteraryagent for making this all possible! 🕺 📚 🐉
Happy New Year from the big 🍎 Hope you find a dance floor wherever you are 🎆 🙏🏽 🕺

Working on the script for @city_of_dragons 3 (don’t worry 2 is coming first!) and I thought I’d snap a cute cafe update image. It wasn’t until I looked at the photo that I saw the dragon face in the foam. see it? They’re EVERYWHERE. Or I’m losing it 🙃🐉✨#wakingup #dragons #amwriting

Trying to find a different kind of shelter from the storm. These are few and far between and this isn’t me. I belly flopped on my chances :-) but still had a blast and managed to catch this clip as I was leaving. Thank you mama Ocean you are magic and I love you 🙏🏽❤️🙏🏽❤️ Stay safe out there friends. It’s about to get wild ⛈️

Don’t worry mom. I’m not paddling out today! Hard to get a sense of the magnitude of this storm swell from video but if you turn the sound up, just the vibrations shake your phone so you can imagine being here. I had to dodge a splash on that last clip 😅 Otters, however, don’t seem bothered. I keep catching them snacking between 30 foot waves. All your perspective, I guess, but from a human view it’s humbling. Stay safe. #california #storm #bomb-cyclone #climatechange
Clarity after the storm. Grateful that nature keeps catching me when I fall 🙏🏽❤️🌊

Fin broke his arm a few weeks ago but ya can’t hold back a stoked 7-year-old. He inspires all of us with his cheerfulness and creativity. We couldn’t find an open court the other night, so he and Eben made up this dribbling drill. They are way better than me at basketball but I tried. Don’t laugh.  I’m sticking to surfing 😆🏀 🥊

Today is the day! Mop Rides the Waves of Courage - the third in the @mop_rides picture book series - is out now. I’ve loved working on all these books but this one might be my favorite. Maybe because Mop learns to deal with anxiety which has been a huge part of my journey. Or maybe because we get to meet Mop’s rad dad, or maybe it’s the animals. I don’t know but this adventure gets me choked up in the best way when I read it. If you enjoyed Mop so far I think you’ll really love this one. But if you don’t know Mop yet, this is a fine book to start with (not a mystery series :-) As always, @mattallen_art put so much love into illustrating every page.  Grab one wherever you get your books! Link in my bio to multiple options. 
Huge thanks to the team @parallaxpress @penguinrandomhouse and @markgottliebliteraryagent @trident_media for being the wind in our sails on this.

Life imitating art... and kicking you in the ass. After focusing the third @mop_rides book on courage - Mop's dad helps him work through nerves in the ocean  and school - I've found myself facing some of my biggest waves of anxiety and fear living far inland in Washington DC and wondering who I am at 43 (thank you to everyone who wrote supportive comments on my last post -  healing). After venting, I thought I’d say the good news about being kicked down like this is that you have the opportunity to learn the basics all over again. I've been pointed back in fresh ways to the RAIN method @tarabrach  teaches so beautifully. If you're not familiar, basically when you have a big wave of emotion…let it RAIN:

* Recognize what is happening;
* Allow the experience to be there, just as it is;
* Investigate with interest and care;
* Nurture with self-compassion.

This is basically the meditation Mop is learning from his dad here, and it sounds easy enough to put in a kid’s book, but it's anything but easy because when big waves of fear or grief come we often want to do the other R - RUN. When we do have the courage to breathe, accept and feel, the self compassion part is tricky too because sometimes the compassionate thing to do is to let yourself just be / relax, and sometimes the compassionate thing is to take action of some sort (join a book club, get therapy etc). A lot of times it’s both or a spectrum. It's a process but I just thought I'd say I still think RAIN is a really good one and easy to remember. In reading Tara Brach's approach to RAIN I came across a beautiful Rumi poem she quotes in her pieces on facing fear (that I recommend).

Life’s water flows from darkness.
Search the darkness don’t run from it.
Night travelers are full of light,
and you are, too; don’t leave this companionship. ~ 
Rumi

You are already free. A common Zen teaching but Variations of this insight have been bouncing around for thousands of years from poets and mystics and philosophers of different cultures. The notion that our current situation- warts and worries and all - is already divine, enlightened, fully liberated. We just have to wake up to that reality. Breathe - KABOOM! Can’t say I get it but it has intrigued me for years and has been repeating for me all week so it felt like time to share the words again. Already free? What does it mean to you? 

In the busy busy, it feels far away and abstract. What I need is to catch up on work and sleep and fill my bank account and get a break from breaking up my kids bickering. That would be free! But if I let myself (or force myself :) to slow down and feel the feelings, breathe the breaths it starts hitting different. How is this wave of worry / not enoughness actually the ocean of total creativity / life / love? How can my deficiencies be okay like peeling bark on a tree or a wilting leaf that will nourish the next sapling? And am I actually appreciating the breeze, health, this food, this sensation, what’s here? If I’m not totally free right now, Am I at least more free than I THINK? (That’s definitely true since my thoughts are a tangle!) 

It’s an interesting notion that I’m still finding helpful to experiment with. Interested to hear how it hits you. What’s your experience with this idea - if you’ve worked with it for a while or just hearing it…

Washington DC, you shall not stop Dad from soft top botching floaters and mush tubes in abundance this summer! Seriously grateful to my wife and family for helping us schedule lots of summer time at the beach. What did I learn being away so much? Well, besides that I’m out of paddle shape, I learned all that stuff about surfing being a healing therapy is not just a cliche surfers trot out to justify the obsession. See, I wasn’t just making it up! Surfing really is a powerful anti-depressant / yoga / wellness bonanza (in addition to a rad sport). So if you’re at all taking it for granted or feeling not stoked on surfing, move away from the ocean for a bit - or imagine you did - and it should help a bunch. Yes, Gerry, surf is where you find it, and I will continue looking for it in the quantum waves and at the grocery store, but it’s certainly not bad when you find it at the ocean. 🤙 🤙 🤙

#surf #therapy #oceanlove #saltwater #healing

We managed to escape down here to Jacksonville Beach where Eben and Fin are proving it’s never too small for big smiles and Grammy is proving she’s our family surf photographer. Another upside to the tiny - paddling into their own waves and no stress for Mom while reading on shore. Awesome cheerleading from Auntie @lilciciblue is also a major bonus. Yesterday, Eben even quoted @mop_rides - “Not this one Dad. I’m waiting for just the right wave to ride.” Dad heaven. #familysurftrip #vitaminsea #gromsquad #surf #mopridesthewavesoflife #moreplease

Mom and me in our happy place 🐚🌊💙 Was very, very hot in Jacksonville Beach this week but those evening walks and morning longboards…Thank you. Revisiting my post a couple months ago on pining for the sea living inland: I can report yet again that it wasn’t a false alarm. Getting to the waves - no matter how mini - is such a powerful salve for me; i almost feel shallow that it works so damn well. I also find it’s a lot easier for me to get writing done when I can surf so - haha - now I have a work excuse. Yep, should be getting a writing bonus for these trips 😁. Flow neuro-scientists back me up here! 

I do think living inland for some time is a good psychological and spiritual challenge- that which doesn’t kill you… And family time is very good. But also maybe mama universe is showing me (all over again) what it means to be an ocean person in your bones? Can’t shake that out! Recognize. That IS what you’re saying- right …? 💫 

That’s how I’m reading the waves of emotional hieroglyphics anyway. So now to deal with climate guilt about these surf trips. We do at least have an EV but I need to get volunteering / fundraising for @sea.trees to offset some road trippin’. 🌊 🌳 Planning LOTS. You know, for work… 🚌

Just picked up our fourth boy! This guy and his siblings were left in a box on the side of the road in Texas. Some angel caregivers drove him up to a foster farm in Maryland and he came home with us yesterday. Sweetest puppy ever - mix of lab, husky and Alaskan Malamute. We are all googoo in love.

It’s not quite the salty brine but the Potomac can pretty damn gorgeous and restorative. Captain Finnie Yogis and I took our maiden tandem voyage from Maryland to Virginia a couple days ago on the SUP and I’ve been experimenting with riding- i.e. eating it - on the mini rapids. First tries with the puppy - now named Roman - failed miserably and lost my phone in the river jumping in after him, but determined to keep it going. hopefully some more freshwater Buddha reporting to come. Have any of y’all done this river SUP thing? I’m a full kook out here

Fin and I snuck out for some Virginia waves and I thought I got a parking ticket on the van when we came in. Turned out it was a note from photographer @mri_craig who’d snapped some photos of us and wanted to share - no charge. He left us his email and sent these wonderful memories of a special 1 on 1 trip. Thank you Craig! Truly a kind thing to do.

Just learned from reporting in @theatlantic that my books  also seem to have been used without permission or payment to populate AI. While this is new territory and I’m no lawyer, this strikes me as outright theft and copyright infringement. I join in solidarity with @sarahkatesilverman @michael.chabon @elissa_altman (thank you for bringing this to my attention) and many others who believe this is wrong and detrimental to art and artists everywhere. I’m not against AI if it is used for good but if it’s very foundation is based on stealing from artists - who are already often struggling - that’s a deeply negative karmic trajectory. Needs immediate attention from lawmakers, publishers, journalists.

“I’m not striving for the ideal surfer’s paradise anymore, or the perfect life without obstacles. It doesn’t exist. Not that I don’t have preferences or dreams anymore. But it seems like the idea of paradise is just on the horizon, always, while life is here, under my feet, now. 

Might as well enjoy it, learn to appreciate the good waves, the paddling, the ferocious storms, and the mundane moments - the quiet lulls between swells.”
- Jaimal Yogis

We used to come to Pismo Beach as a family growing up. We loved how 1950s and unpretentious it was. It was one of the first places I caught a wave. So it was pretty special to get to extend a west coast book tour into a 75th birthday jam for my mom. I love that the place has barely changed. The older I get the more I realize how special these brief windows of leisure and family are. Big big thank yous to Amy and fam for holding down the fort on the east coast. Reminder from @mop_rides: when those uncomfortable, scary feelings come, take a breath and feel them. Knee jerk reaction is usually to distract ourselves (and sometimes that’s called for) but it can be amazingly freeing when you catch yourself tangled up in an emotion and then, instead of resisting it or running, you feel…

sensations in the body. Arising… passing away. It’s kind of a miracle that with practice, humans have the ability to watch our own emotions and gain distance from them. Profound as the sea… Keep breathing, friends. 

Thanks Mop!

Roman. We “rescued” this guy just a few months ago and I was admittedly very nervous to take on more responsibility, but I’m so glad we did. Roman has definitely been much more our family rescuer. From connecting us to the nature in new ways to bringing out the nurturing side of three competitive brothers to reminding us to say hello with a wag to everyone you pass to helping snuggle us down to sleep, Roman has truly been a gift to our family. Therapy dog, buddy, 4th bro. There is a saying I heard from a Buddhist scholar that dogs are sometimes considered the embodiment of the next Buddha. In any case… paws together 🙏🏽🐾

Had a blast speaking at our 6th grader Kai’s @mcleanschoolofmd  yesterday. Kai told me to “keep it brief,” meaning he has fully entered middle school and is now worried dad might embarrass him. Fortunately the class got so into the dragon discussion, the librarian had to cut off the questions. Kai gave me the sly high five and “nice job” afterward. Phew 😅 #cityofdragons #graphicnovel #series #middlegrade #bookstagram #riseoftheshadowfire #theawakeningstorm #dragons

If you’re looking to get into meditation or go deeper with your practice, you might enjoy the series I taught with @inspirecourses @theinertia that uses ocean and surfing metaphors quite a bit (surprise surprise). No  surfing or meditation experience required  and it’s a gift you don’t have to ship :-) These are ancient techniques that we now have scientific evidence really work to improve mental and physical health. Hope my little spin on them is helpful.
